pressed as the sum of three consecutive integers, return an empty array.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: num = 33\nOutput: [10,11,12]\nExplanation: 33 can be expressed as 10 + 11 + 12 = 33.\n10, 11, 12 are 3 consecutive integers, so we return [10, 11, 12].\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: num = 4\nOutput: []\nExplanation: There is no way to express 4 as the sum of 3 consecutive integers.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n0 <= num <= 1015\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def sumOfThree(self, num: int) -> List[int]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def sumOfThree(self, num: int) -> List[int]:\n        # For three consecutive integers x-1, x, x+1 to sum to num:\n        # (x-1) + x + (x+1) = num\n        # 3x = num\n        # x = num / 3\n        # x must be an integer, so num must be divisible by 3\n        if num % 3 == 0:\n            x = num // 3\n            return [x-1, x, x+1]\n        else:\n            return []\n```\n\nThis solution checks if the given number `num` is divisible by 3. If it is, it calculates the middle integer `x` and returns the three consecutive integers `[x-1, x, x+1]`. If `num` is not divisible by 3, it returns an empty list as it is not possible to express `num` as the sum of three consecutive integers.", "estimated_date": 1644710400000}